**a.** First, we need to remember that an accounting break-even refers to the point wherein the business generates exactly zero profit. In order to solve for the accounting break-even point, we can use this formula: 

$$\begin{aligned}
Q&=\dfrac{FC+D}{P-v}
\end{aligned}$$

where,
$$\begin{aligned}
FC&=\text{Fixed cost}\\
D&=\text{Depreciation}\\
P&=\text{Price per unit}\\
v&=\text{Variable cost per unit}
\end{aligned}$$

The degree of operating leverage refers to the degree of change in the company's income with respect to the change in number of units sold. 

This can be solved using the formula:

$$\begin{aligned}
DOL&=1+\dfrac{FC}{OCF}
\end{aligned}$$

Where, 

$$\begin{aligned}
FC&=\text{Fixed cost}\\
OCF&=\text{Operating cash flow}
\end{aligned}$$

**b.** The base-case operating cashflow is the cashflow wherein the depreciation and the tax rate is placed into consideration. We can use this formula to solve for the base-case cashflow.

$$\begin{aligned}
\text{Base-case cashflow}&=OCF \times (1-T)+(T \times D)
\end{aligned}$$

Where,
$$\begin{aligned}
T&=\text{Tax rate}\\
D&=\text{Depreciation}
\end{aligned}$$
